<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1727,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1836,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Comments.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation box="[496,1046,1836,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" refId="ref21531" refString="Mathur, R. N. (1975) Psyllidae of the Indian subcontinent. Indian Council of Agricultural Research, New Delhi, 429 pp." type="book">Mathur (1975: 31, comment by F. Ossiannilsson)</bibRefCitation>
and (
<bibRefCitation pageId="1" pageNumber="2" refId="ref18186" refString="Burckhardt, D. &amp; Lauterer, P. (1997) Systematics and biology of the Aphalara exilis (Weber and Mohr) species assemblage (Hemiptera: Psyllidae). Entomologica Scandinavica, 28, 271 - 305. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631297 X 00088" type="journal article">Burckhardt &amp; Lauterer 1997: 291</bibRefCitation>
) the Indian populations identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Low" authorityYear="1886" box="[652,920,1871,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Aphalara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis box="[652,920,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Aphalara maculipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may not be conspecific with European 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Low" authorityYear="1886" class="Insecta" family="Psyllidae" genus="Aphalara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculipennis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">A. maculipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We examined one female from Kashmir (BMNH) which looks, however, like European specimens. More material is required to solve this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
